[actions performed]
- Committed milestone 1.6.1 delivery as `c0e28f3 Deliver milestone 1.6.1 adapter boundary and runtime resilience`.
- Rebuilt `app`, `worker`, and `migrate` images and recreated the host stack with `docker compose --profile edge`.
- Verified app readiness on `http://192.168.10.71:7005/readyz` and interactive docs on `http://192.168.10.71:7005/api/swagger`.
- Verified reverse proxy readiness on `https://127.0.0.1:7003/readyz` and `https://127.0.0.1:7003/api/swagger`.
- Identified that `nginx` remained in `health: starting` because the healthcheck used `localhost`, which resolved to IPv6 and failed against an IPv4-only listener.
- Corrected `nginx` healthchecks in `docker-compose.yml`, `docker-compose-release.yml`, and `docker-compose-dev.yml` to probe `127.0.0.1`.

[important commands]
- `docker compose --profile edge down`
- `docker compose --profile edge up -d --build --force-recreate postgres redis`
- `docker compose --profile edge run --rm migrate`
- `docker compose --profile edge up -d --build --force-recreate app worker nginx`
- `docker inspect ioc-service-nginx-1 --format '{{json .State.Health}}'`

[observations]
- The previous host failure (`postgres` DNS resolution inside `app`, then `nginx` upstream resolution to `app`) disappeared after recreating the compose network and services.
- The standalone app port is intentionally bound to `192.168.10.71:7005`; probing `127.0.0.1:7005` is expected to fail on this host.

[mistakes and lessons]
- A container healthcheck that uses `localhost` can silently switch to IPv6 lookup and fail even while the service is healthy on IPv4. Lesson: prefer explicit `127.0.0.1` in Docker healthchecks unless the service is verified to listen on both stacks.
- For HTTPS-only reverse proxies with self-signed certificates, probing plain HTTP readiness can follow a redirect into TLS verification failure. Lesson: point the healthcheck directly at the local TLS endpoint and disable certificate verification for the in-container self-probe.

[next planned implementation steps]
- Recreate `nginx` with the corrected healthcheck and confirm all services are healthy.
- Commit the healthcheck correction.
- Tag and publish release `1.6.1`, then push branch and tag.

